source_code.code:
public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		System.out.println(SWT.getPlatform());
	}
}

public class Main {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		new Main().test();
	}

	int count= 0;
	private void test() {
		count++;
		count++;
		count++;
		
	}
}

Bug.WithStack:
2.1 RC1

1. Put a breakpoint in the first line of test();
2. If you look at the value of count in the variables view, it should (a) 
change value and (b) be colored red.  

The count variable is not being colored red.
In 2.0, the variable was colored red.

public class Main {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		new Main().test();
	}

	int count= 0;
	private void test() {
		count++;
		count++;
		count++;
		
	}
}
Fixed. Problem was in JDIStackFrame#updateVariables(). We were always replacing 
the 'this' variable with a new object since the receiver could have changed (we 
cache stack frames - so when hitting a breakpoint in a method, that is called 
from a loop, we could be in a different receiver). However, we only need to 
replace the 'this' variable when 'this' has actually changed.

Thus, the model was always saying that the value had not changed, since it was 
always a new object and had no previous state to compare to.

please verify, Luc.
Added JUnit test - InstanceVariableTests#testValueHasChanged()
Verified.

